column263: I honed my strategy  over the experiment. At the end  my strategy was as follows: | In the beginning of each path  I put slightly more money into asset A  approximately 60%. If my returns were high  I'd invest approximately the same percentage into asset A  but if low  I wouldn't invest less money. I purchased asset C if I had a large exess of funds  and I almost always viewed the top investor of my co-experimentees when given the option.
I didnt like how your payment was random. It is pretty fustrating because 90% of this experiment is luck.
it was very fun! I looked at the amount i had and then made a decision based on how much i was willing to lose.
Some part probability - tried to follow the bar graph  but when the grid scale kept changing it threw me off- especially with only 6 seconds to decide.

I tried to make up to a certain amount of money and then keep that much money until the end. I ingnored the $20 4% button after realizing that it would cost more on average than the payout. Sometimes I'd gamble and lose or win  but I tried to stay somewhat consistent.
Guessing. Trying to invest carefully when I had little. Not really a risk taker type. |  | I was confused on the purpose of the 3rd part (showing lowest/avg/highest).

I tended to be conservative for the first period  always investing more in Asset B than Asset A. Then I would try to look at the varying multipliers and predict what would come next. If there were successive periods of of all high multipliers  I became more careful and put more money in Asset B  if there were multiple periods with low multipliers  I put more money in Asset A because I predicted the next period would be higher. I set my goal amount for each period to be $5 and I switched between Asset A and Asset B accordingly. Once I reached my $5 goal  I became more free with my spending  puttin gmore money in Asset A.
Since it depends only on luck  I just randomly choose the percentage of the two assets.

I made investment decisions pretty arbitrarily. Initially I tried looking for trends in the asset A multiplier  but that led to very little success. Towards the end I began investing 1 or 2 dollar amounts into A and protecting the rest in B. This led to significantly better results. Also I at first used percentages of my account to use investment decisions  but i eventually moved to using the dollar amount because I tended to be less risky that way.

I tried being pretty conservative for the most part but took occasional risks when I thought the return for Asset A was going to be big. Sometimes it paid off  sometimes it didn't. Overall  I'm content with how I did  but wish I did better in Parts 2&3
